54-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofgreekfi00part }}\n*Saunders, J.J. -- ''The History of the Mongol Conquests,'' Routledge & Kegan Paul Ltd, 1971, {{ISBN|0-8122-1766-7}}\n*Sicker, Martin -- ''The Islamic World in Ascendancy: From the Arab Conquests to the Siege of Vienna,'' Praeger Publishers, 2000\n*Soucek, Svatopluk -- ''A History of Inner Asia'', Cambridge, 2000\n*Verbruggen, J.F. -- ''The Art of Warfare in Western Europe during the Middle Ages'', Boydell Press, Second English translation 1997, {{ISBN|0-85115-570-7}}\n*[[Conn Iggulden|Iggulden, Conn]] -- ''Genghis, Birth of an Empire'', Bantham Dell.\n\n==External links==\nMedieval History: Mongol Invasion of Europe at http://historymedren.about.com/library/prm/bl1mongolinvasion.htm\n{{Mongol Empire}}\n{{Ancient and Dynastic Chinese Military History}}\n{{Commons category|Military of Mongolia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mongol Military Tactics And Organization}}\n[[Category:Military history of the Mongol Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCatapults and machines", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mongol_military_tactics_and_organization"}
{"title_page": "Orna Villa", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Orna Villa\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Orna Villa.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | location= 1008 N. Emory St., [[Oxford, Georgia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|33.62408|N|83.86641|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = USA Georgia#USA\n  | built = 1825\n  | architect = Richard K. Dearing\n  | architecture = [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]\n  | added = January 29, 1973\n  | area = {{convert|1.8|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 73000636<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Orna Villa''', also known as the '''Alexander Means House''' and the '''Means/Tanner House''', is a historic [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]] house located on Emory Street in [[Oxford, Georgia]].  Built in 1825, it is the oldest house in Oxford. The house is a work of Richard K. Dearing.\n\nThe home was owned for a time by Alexander Means, a founder and president of Emory College (the original site of which is now [[Oxford College of Emory University]]) and was used as a hospital during the [[American Civil War]].  The house has been featured in works on haunted houses because of its alleged association with the ghost of [[Tobe Means]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Norman, Beth Scott|title=Historic Haunted America|pages=89\u201390|publisher=Macmillan|year=2007|isbn=0765319705}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Walking Tour of Oxford|publisher=City of Oxford|accessdate=August 8, 2012|url=http://oxfordgeorgia.org/index.php/walkingtour}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phantom Folklore: Orna Villa|newspaper=Covington News|author=Amber Pittman|date=October 24, 2010|url=http://www.covnews.com/archives/15109/}}</ref> The house was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP) in 1973.<ref name=nris/> Orna Villa was the location of a college frat party in ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.covnews.com/section/1/article/32467/|title=\u2018Vampire Diaries\u2019 films for 4th season|newspaper=Covington News|accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref>\n\nIt is a [[contributing building]] within the [[Oxford Historic District (Oxford, Georgia)|Oxford Historic District]] which also is NRHP-listed.<ref name=nris/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [https://rose.library.emory.edu/ Stuart A. Rose Manuscript, Archives, and Rare Book Library], Emory University: [http://pid.emory.edu/ark:/25593/8zncp Alexander Means papers, 1824-1963]\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival houses in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1825]]\n[[Category:Houses in Newton County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Newton County, Georgia]]\n\n\n{{GeorgiaUS-NRHP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Orna Villa\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Orna Villa.JPG\n  | caption = \n  | location= 1008 N. Emory St., [[Oxford, Georgia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|33.62408|N|83.86641|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = USA Georgia#USA\n  | built = 1825\n  | architect = Richard K. Dearing\n  | architecture = [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]\n  | added = January 29, 1973\n  | area = {{convert|1.8|acre}}\n  | governing_body = Private \n  | refnum = 73000636<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Orna Villa''', also known as the '''Alexander Means House''' and the '''Means/Tanner House''', is a historic [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]] house located on Emory Street in [[Oxford, Georgia]].  Built in 1825, it is the oldest house in Oxford. The house is a work of Richard K. Dearing.\n\nThe home was owned for a time by Alexander Means, a founder and president of Emory College (the original site of which is now [[Oxford College of Emory University]]) and was used as a hospital during the [[American Civil War]].  The house has been featured in works on haunted houses because of its alleged association with the ghost of [[Tobe Means]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Norman, Beth Scott|title=Historic Haunted America|pages=89\u201390|publisher=Macmillan|year=2007|isbn=0765319705}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Walking Tour of Oxford|publisher=City of Oxford|accessdate=August 8, 2012|url=http://oxfordgeorgia.org/index.php/walkingtour}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Phantom Folklore: Orna Villa|newspaper=Covington News|author=Amber Pittman|date=October 24, 2010|url=http://www.covnews.com/archives/15109/}}</ref> The house was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] (NRHP) in 1973.<ref name=nris/> Orna Villa was the location of a college frat party in ''[[The Vampire Diaries]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.covnews.com/section/1/article/32467/|title=\u2018Vampire Diaries\u2019 films for 4th season|newspaper=Covington News|accessdate=2012-10-20}}</ref>\n\nIt is a [[contributing building]] within the [[Oxford Historic District (Oxford, Georgia)|Oxford Historic District]] which also is NRHP-listed.<ref name=nris/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival houses in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1825]]\n[[Category:Houses in Newton County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Newton County, Georgia]]\n\n\n{{GeorgiaUS-NRHP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "A.C.Butner", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orna_Villa"}
{"title_page": "Ministry of Justice (Poland)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = Ministry of Justice\n|nativename      = <small>Ministerstwo Sprawiedliwo\u015bci</small>\n|logo            = Logo ms RP.gif\n|logo_width      = 250px\n|logo_caption    = Ministerial logotype\n|seal            = Polish Governmental and Diplomatic Plaque.svg\n|seal_width      = 150px\n|seal_caption    = Official governmental wall plaque  \n|image           = Warszawafc7.jpg\n|image_caption   = The seat of the Ministry of Justice at 11 [[Ujazd\u00f3w Avenue|Al. Ujazdowskie]], opposite the [[Sejm]] in central [[Warsaw]]\n|formed          =\n|preceding1      = \n|preceding2      =\n|jurisdiction    =\n|headquarters    = [[Ujazd\u00f3w Avenue|Al. Ujazdowskie 11]], [[Warsaw]]\n|employees       = \n|budget          =\n|chief1_name     = [[Zbigniew Ziobro]]\n|chief1_position = Minister of Justice\n|chief2_name     = [[Patryk Jaki]]\n|chief2_position = First Deputy Minister\n|parent_agency   = [[Council of Ministers of the Republic of Poland|Council of Ministers]]\n|website         = [http://www.ms.gov.pl/ www.ms.gov.pl]\n|footnotes       =\n}}\n\n'''The Ministry of Justice of the Republic of Poland''' is one of the [[Ministries of the Republic of Poland|ministries]] of [[Poland]]. \n\nFrom 1956\u20131957, [[Zofia Wasilkowska]] was the first female to serve as a Minister of Justice in Poland's history.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c0uTDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT363&lpg=PT363&dq|title=New Perspectives on European Women\u2019s Legal History|last=Kimble|first=Sara L.|last2=R\u00f6wekamp|first2=Marion|date=2016-07-01|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317577157|language=en}}</ref>\n\nEach Minister of Justice between 1990 and 2010 was also [[Public Prosecutor General (Poland)|Public Prosecutor General]].\n\n==List of ministers==\n===Ministers of Justice (1989-present)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Portrait\n!Name\n!Party\n! colspan=\"2\" |Term of Office\n![[Prime Minister]] (cabinet)\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Polish People's Party/meta/color}};\"|\n|\n|[[Aleksander Bentkowski]]\n|[[United People's Party (Poland)|United People's Party]]/[[Polish People's Party]]\n|12 September 1989 \n|12 January 1991\n|[[Tadeusz Mazowiecki]] \n\n<small>([[Cabinet of Tadeusz Mazowiecki|Mazowiecki]])</small>\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Christian National Union/meta/color}};\"|\n|[[File:Wies\u0142aw Chrzanowski-polityk (2010).jpg|60px]]\n|[[Wies\u0142aw Chrzanowski]]\n|[[Christian National Union]]\n|12 January 1991\n|25 November 1991\n|[[Jan Krzysztof Bielecki]] \n\n<small>([[Cabinet of Jan Krzysztof Bielecki|Bielecki]])</small>\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Independent/meta/color}};\"|\n|\n|''[[Andrzej Marcinkowski]] (acting)''\n|[[Nonpartisanism|Nonpartisan]]\n|25 November 1991\n|5 December 1991\n|[[Jan Krzysztof Bielecki]] \n\n<small>([[Cabinet of Jan Krzysztof Bielecki|Bielecki]])</small>\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Christian National Union/meta/color}};\"|\n|\n|[[Zbigniew Dyka]]\n|[[Christian National Union]]\n|23 December 1991 \n|17 March 1993\n|[[Jan Olszewski]] \n\n<small>([[Cabinet of Jan Olszewski|Olszewski]]), </small>  \n\n[[Hanna Suchocka]] \n\n<small>([[Cabinet of Hanna Suchocka|Suchocka]])</small> \n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Christian National Union/meta/color}};\"|\n|\n|[[Jan Pi\u0105tkowski]]\n|[[Christian National Union]]\n|17 March 1993\n|26 October 1993\n|[[Hanna Suchocka]] \n<small>([[Cabinet of Hanna Suchocka|Suchocka]])</small> \n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Social Democracy of Poland/meta/color}};\"|\n|[[File:W\u0142odzimierz Cimoszewicz (senator).jpg|60px]]\n|[[W\u0142odzimierz Cimoszewicz]]\n|[[SdRP]]\n|26 March 1993\n|6 March 1995\n|[[Waldemar Pawlak]] \n<small>([[Second Cabinet of Waldemar Pawlak|Pawlak II]])</small> \n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Social Democracy of Poland/meta/color}};\"|\n|\n|[[Jerzy Jaskiernia]]\n|[[SdRP]]\n|6 March 1995\n|7 February 1996\n|[[J\u00f3zef Oleksy]] \n<small>([[Cabinet of J\u00f3zef Ole